Five Truths About Terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in a month.
For ten years, never had so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, although their number is still far below the 46% recorded the day after the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this shift in public opinion were most felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), has undoubtedly benefited from it.
Some politicians feel free to refer to the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But both presidential candidates, as well as some media outlets, who follow the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated its proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists are more concerned with grabbing attention and dominating the political news than with the number, per se, of their victims.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric beheadings broadcast on social networks are intended to destabilize and shock – and therefore to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making headlines with every act of terrorism is playing into the terrorists' hands.
Terrorism is not the greatest threat facing the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills far less than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be murdered by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans run a greater risk of dying in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from an accident caused by a household appliance (a probability of 1 in 1.5 million), from a deer or elk crossing the road (a probability of 1 in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (a probability of 1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving while texting or talking on their mobile phones.
This is several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
World terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to quell a terrorist outbreak.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, groups from the "autonomous" left, hijacked planes out of national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (as well as ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon wrapped in a religious costume.
Many of their leaders are not traditional fundamentalists, but people whose identity has been destroyed by globalization, who seek meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorist movements that preceded it have been.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat it.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in toppling one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking the citizens of a state enough to drive them to futile actions, they can hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda succeeded in drawing Americans to Afghanistan.
ISIS was born in the ruins of the Iraq invasion conducted by the United States, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, smart power is required.
Smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Influence power is also necessary if one wants to "vaccinate" those on the periphery who extremists seek to recruit.
This is why attention to the narrative of events and how the actions of the United States are commented on social media is as important and necessary as precision air strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all at risk.
Reason why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It is an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of the reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by terrorists.
Let us not fill the theater where actions are carried out by thugs and criminals.
If we allow them to take the grand stage of our public speech, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and mislead our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
